1 majority and minority composition of that chamber.
2 (c) Subject to subsection (5)(c), if If the committee workload requires, the legislative council may
3 request the appointing authority to appoint one or two additional interim committee members from the majority
4 party and the minority party.
5 If additional members are appointed, members must be appointed in a manner that reflects the
6 majority and minority composition of the legislature.
7 (d) An interim committee may not have a majority of its members be from the minority party.
8 (6) The membership of the interim committees must be provided for by legislative rules. The rules
9 must identify the committees from which members are selected, and the appointing authority shall attempt to
10 select not less than 50% of the members from the standing committees that consider issues within the
11 jurisdiction of the interim committee and at least one member from the joint subcommittee that considers the
12 related agency budgets. In making the appointments, the appointing authority shall take into account term limits
13 of members so that committee members will be available to follow through on committee activities and
14 recommendations in the next legislative session.
15 (7) An interim committee, the environmental quality council, or the modernization and risk analysis
16 committee may create subcommittees. Nonlegislative members may serve on a subcommittee. Unless the
17 person is a full-time salaried officer or employee of the state or a political subdivision of the state, a
18 nonlegislative member appointed to a subcommittee or to the modernization and risk analysis committee is
19 entitled to salary and expenses to the same extent as a legislative member. If the appointee is a full-time
20 salaried officer or employee of the state or of a political subdivision of the state, the appointee is entitled to
21 reimbursement for travel expenses as provided for in 2-18-501 through 2-18-503."
22
23 Section 2. Section 5-5-234, MCA, is amended to read:
24 "5-5-234. Appointments. (1) (a) Whenever a legislative appointing authority is required or authorized
25 to appoint more than one legislative member of the majority party to a committee, subcommittee, or other
26 statutorily recognized or authorized entity, the appointing authority may appoint a member of a party other than
27 the majority party.
28 (b) Whenever a legislative appointing authority is required or authorized to appoint more than one
- 2 - LC 1398

