1 legislative member of the minority party to a committee, subcommittee, other statutorily recognized or
2 authorized entity, the appointing authority may, if requested by the minority leader, appoint a member of a party
3 other than the minority party or majority party instead of a member of the minority party.
4 (2) (a) Whenever an elected state official, as defined in 5-7-102, is required or authorized to
5 appoint more than one legislative member of the majority party to a statutorily recognized or authorized entity,
6 the elected state official may, if requested by the senate president for a senate appointee or if requested by the
7 speaker of the house for a house appointee, appoint a member of a party other than the majority party instead
8 of a member of the majority party.
9 (b) Whenever an elected state official, as defined in 5-7-102, is required or authorized to appoint
10 more than one legislative member of the minority party to a statutorily recognized or authorized entity, the
11 elected state official may, if requested by the senate minority leader for a senate appointee or if requested by
12 the house minority leader for a house appointee, appoint a member of a party other than the minority party or
13 majority party instead of a member of the minority party.
14 (3) If a vacancy occurs in the membership of a committee, subcommittee, or statutorily recognized
15 or authorized entity because of the resignation or disqualification of a member appointed under the provisions
16 of subsection (1) or (2), the appointing authority authorized or required to make an appointment to fill the
17 vacancy is subject to the provisions of subsections (1) and (2).
18 (4) If an individual appointed under subsection (1) or (2) is not a member of either the majority
19 party or minority party and resigns from or is otherwise disqualified from serving, the appointing authority shall
20 fill the vacancy under the provisions of subsection (1) or (2) as if the appointment were an initial appointment,
21 and the appointing authority is not required to fill the vacancy with an individual who is a member of the same
22 party of which the individual whose resignation or disqualification caused the vacancy.
23 (5) The appointing authority for an interim committee provided for in Title 5 and composed of nine
24 or more members shall appoint members in a manner that reflects the majority and minority composition of the
25 legislature as provided in 5-5-211(5)(b) through (5)(d)."
